# SELF-ASSESSMENT

## 1. Overview

This section summarizes my self-assessment after completing the AWS Cloud Computing internship and participating in the AWS Stock Analyzer project.

During the internship, I learned basic AWS cloud concepts, reviewed several AWS services, and participated in the final project as a QA Tester.
My main contribution was not advanced system implementation, but manual testing and project review support.

Through this process, I gained a better understanding of AWS services, cloud-based application architecture, and the role of testing in a software project.

---

## 2. Knowledge Gained

During the internship, I learned the basic purpose of several AWS services, including IAM, EC2, S3, VPC, Security Groups, Lambda, API Gateway, SQS, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, and Amazon Bedrock.

In the first weeks, I mainly followed tutorials and reviewed learning materials to understand AWS fundamentals.
From Week 7, I started connecting this knowledge with the AWS Stock Analyzer project.

The most important knowledge I gained includes:

* Basic cloud computing concepts.
* The role of AWS services in a cloud application.
* Basic serverless architecture.
* Frontend and backend communication through APIs.
* Data storage using Amazon S3 and DynamoDB.
* Monitoring and logging using Amazon CloudWatch.
* The importance of testing before final project submission.

Although my understanding is still at a beginner level, I can now read and understand a basic AWS architecture diagram more clearly than before.

---

## 3. Skills Improved

### 3.1 AWS Basic Understanding

I improved my ability to recognize common AWS services and understand their basic roles in a system.
For example, I learned that S3 can be used for file storage, Lambda can run backend logic, API Gateway can expose APIs, and CloudWatch can support monitoring.

### 3.2 Manual Testing Skills

As the QA Tester in the AWS Stock Analyzer project, I practiced basic manual testing activities, including:

* Testing frontend interface behavior.
* Testing backend API responses.
* Checking valid and invalid input cases.
* Checking frontend-backend integration.
* Recording testing observations.
* Giving feedback to the team.

This helped me understand that testing is not only about finding errors, but also about checking whether the system works as expected from the user’s perspective.

### 3.3 Documentation Skills

I also improved my documentation skills by writing weekly worklogs, project proposal content, posted blog summaries, and testing-related notes.
This helped me organize my learning process and present my work more clearly.

---

## 4. My Contribution to the Project

In the AWS Stock Analyzer project, my assigned role was QA Tester.

My main contributions included:

* Understanding the project features and testing scope.
* Preparing basic testing directions.
* Testing backend API behavior.
* Testing frontend interface behavior.
* Testing input validation cases.
* Checking frontend-backend integration.
* Recording final testing observations.
* Supporting the team during final project review.

My contribution was mainly focused on manual testing.
I did not claim to build the whole AWS infrastructure alone.
Instead, I supported the team by checking the system behavior and helping identify issues before final submission.

---

## 5. Difficulties and Limitations

During the internship, I faced several difficulties.

First, AWS has many services, and it was difficult to understand all of them deeply in a short time.
Some services were easy to understand at a basic level, but harder to apply in a complete project.

Second, from Week 3 to Week 5, I mainly watched YouTube tutorials and read materials, so I did not have much hands-on practice during that period.
Because of that, my practical experience was still limited.

Third, as a QA Tester, I mainly performed manual testing.
I did not use advanced automation testing tools or write complex test scripts.

These limitations showed me that I still need more practice with AWS implementation, backend testing, and automated testing in the future.

---

## 6. What I Did Well

I think I did well in the following areas:

* I followed the internship learning process and recorded my weekly progress.
* I reviewed AWS basic concepts and connected them with the final project.
* I completed my assigned QA testing tasks for the AWS Stock Analyzer project.
* I tested the main application flow manually.
* I documented my work honestly without overstating my experience.
* I improved my understanding of how a cloud-based application is structured.

Although my technical level is still basic, I was able to complete my assigned role and contribute to the project review process.

---

## 7. What I Need to Improve

After completing this internship, I realized that I need to improve in several areas:

* Practice AWS services more through hands-on labs.
* Learn more about backend API testing.
* Improve my understanding of serverless deployment.
* Learn basic automation testing tools.
* Improve my ability to read logs and troubleshoot cloud application issues.
* Practice writing clearer test cases and bug reports.

These improvements will help me become more confident in future software development and cloud computing projects.

---

## 8. Overall Reflection

Overall, this internship helped me gain a basic but useful understanding of AWS Cloud Computing.
I learned how different AWS services can support a cloud-based application and how a project can be divided into frontend, backend, database, processing, AI analysis, and monitoring layers.

Through the AWS Stock Analyzer project, I also understood the importance of the QA Tester role.
Testing helped me review the system from the user’s perspective and check whether the main features worked as expected.

Although my experience is still at a beginner level, I completed my assigned testing responsibilities and learned many useful concepts for future projects.
This internship gave me a clearer direction for improving my cloud computing, software testing, and project documentation skills.
